data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The **sync-over-async opt-in for the EF Core Cosmos DB provider is removed**. In .NET 10, you could call something like:

```csharp
options.UseCosmos(..., cosmosOptions => cosmosOptions.AllowSynchronousIO());
```

In .NET 11, that API no longer exists. All four of your repository methods will throw **`InvalidOperationException`** at runtime because the Cosmos DB SDK is inherently async — there is no synchronous I/O path anymore.

## What to fix

Convert every sync call to its async counterpart:

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- `ToList()` → `ToListAsync()`
- `First()` → `FirstAsync()`
- `Count()` → `CountAsync()`
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- All callers up the chain must also go async

> **Note:** This only affects the **Cosmos DB provider**. The relational providers (SQL Server, PostgreSQL, etc.) still support synchronous APIs. If you have a mixed-provider app, only the Cosmos paths need migration.
